  "texts": [
    "A common flaw in trigger-based attacks is training solely on effective triggers without incorporating deviated samples, leading to a high false trigger rate (FTR), i.e., the likelihood of unintended activations.",
    "To evaluate this, we test how partial or scrambled combinations of trigger components lead to mistake activations.",
    "As shown in Figure 3, without PAG, FTR exceeds 80%, meaning most incomplete or misordered triggers still bypass system prompts.",
    "Enforcing only component presence reduces FTR to 21.70%, while enforcing only correct ordering lowers it to 10%.",
    "Only comprehensive PAG, ensuring both conditions, eliminates FTR (0%) and prevents unintended activations."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}